{
  "card_id": "reversal_vs_continuation",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Reversal vs Continuation",
  "aliases": [
    "Next Candle Model",
    "Next Day Model",
    "previous candle model",
    "Previous Candle Model"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A reversal occurs when price takes out the previous candle's high or low but closes back inside its range, signaling a potential opposite move next. A continuation occurs when price closes outside the range, signaling the trend will persist. The model uses the previous candle's close relative to its range to predict the next candle's direction, with reliability enhanced by PD arrays, swing points, and price delivery phases.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify whether the previous candle takes out its high or low.",
    "Confirm the close position: close back inside the range indicates a failed breakout (reversal signal); close outside the range indicates a successful breakout (continuation signal).",
    "A failed breakout predicts the next candle to move opposite to the breakout direction; a successful breakout predicts continuation in the same direction.",
    "If price takes out the low but closes inside the range, expect next candle to open low and close high (bullish reversal).",
    "If price takes out the high but closes inside the range, expect next candle to open high and close low (bearish reversal).",
    "Check if the previous candle respects PD arrays (FVG, OB, etc.) or swing points; failure to close beyond that structure triggers reversal expectation.",
    "Align with phases of price delivery (expansion, manipulation, retracement) to filter signals.",
    "Must wait for the previous candle to fully close before judging direction.",
    "If a swing point is taken but the close is inside, treat as a conflict and wait for another candle."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Provides a bias framework for the next candle: a reversal close anticipates a move opposite the break; a continuation close anticipates a move in the same direction. Use with points of interest (order blocks, fair value gaps) and confirmation of change in state of delivery on lower time frames to enter with defined risk and targets. Can drill down to hourly or 15-minute charts for specific entries, using prior day high/low or swing points as stops and targets.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Mechanically applying the model without considering price delivery phase, leading to counter-trend trades in expansion.",
    "Not waiting for the previous candle to fully close before predicting the next candle's direction.",
    "Ignoring the close position and only looking at whether high/low was taken (must close inside for reversal).",
    "Not confirming that price truly respected PD arrays or swing points, relying on visual judgment alone.",
    "Trading when multiple signals conflict (e.g., swing point sweep vs. inside close) without waiting for more confirmation.",
    "Ignoring higher-order structures like Market Structure Shift (MSS), causing predictions to fail.",
    "Expecting the pattern to work 100% of the time without additional confluences.",
    "Applying the model in unstable market structures, leading to failed expectations."
  ],
